---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Getting started &middot; peek">
  <h1>Getting started</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Run the MCP server, point your AI client at it, load the extension.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Requires Node.js 22 or newer.</strong> peek&apos;s native
    <code>better-sqlite3</code> dependency only ships prebuilt binaries for Node 22+;
    on Node 20 (notably on Windows, which has no C/C++ build toolchain by default)
    the install falls back to compiling from source and fails. Check with
    <code>node --version</code> before you start.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Run the MCP server</h2>
  <p>
    The simplest path is <code>npx</code> &mdash; no install needed. Your AI client will
    spawn the server for you on demand:
  </p>
  <pre><code>npx -y @peekdev/mcp@latest</code></pre>
  <p>
    This runs the stdio MCP server (it reads and writes the local SQLite at
    <code>~/.peek/sessions.db</code>). You generally won&apos;t invoke it directly &mdash;
    your AI client (next step) does that.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <code>@latest</code> tag is required while peek is in alpha: every published
    version is a prerelease (<code>0.1.0-alpha.*</code>), and a bare
    <code>npx -y @peekdev/mcp</code> resolves the implicit <code>*</code> range, which
    doesn&apos;t match prereleases (<code>ETARGET: No matching version found</code>).
    Pinning <code>@latest</code> forces the newest published build.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Configure your AI client</h2>
  <p>
    Add peek as an MCP server in your client&apos;s config. Pick the one you use:
  </p>

  <h3>Claude Code &mdash; <code>~/.claude.json</code></h3>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "peek": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@peekdev/mcp@latest"]
    }
  }
}
`}</code></pre>

  <h3>Cursor &mdash; <code>~/.cursor/mcp.json</code></h3>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "peek": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@peekdev/mcp@latest"]
    }
  }
}
`}</code></pre>

  <h3>VS Code Copilot &mdash; <code>.vscode/mcp.json</code></h3>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "servers": {
    "peek": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@peekdev/mcp@latest"]
    }
  }
}
`}</code></pre>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Or let the CLI do it all.</strong> Install <code>@peekdev/cli</code> and run
    <code>peek init</code> &mdash; it detects installed AI clients, writes the right
    MCP config for each, <em>and</em> registers the native messaging host with your
    browsers (macOS: <code>~/Library/Application Support/Google/Chrome/NativeMessagingHosts/</code>;
    Linux: <code>~/.config/google-chrome/NativeMessagingHosts/</code>; Windows:
    a registry key under <code>HKCU\\Software\\Google\\Chrome\\NativeMessagingHosts</code>).
    Consent-prompted; you choose which browsers to register.
    <pre style="margin-top: 0.5rem;"><code>npm install -g @peekdev/cli
peek init</code></pre>
  </div>

  <h2>3. Load the Chrome extension (alpha)</h2>
  <p>
    Until the Chrome Web Store listing is live (Phase 5), load the extension
    unpacked from a local build:
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`git clone https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack.git
cd rrweb-stack
pnpm install
pnpm build
pnpm --filter @peekdev/extension build
`}</code></pre>
  <ol>
    <li>Open <code>chrome://extensions</code>.</li>
    <li>Enable <strong>Developer mode</strong> (top right).</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Load unpacked</strong>.</li>
    <li>Select <code>packages/peek-extension/.output/chrome-mv3/</code>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>4. Enable peek on a site</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Open the side panel from the toolbar.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Enable on this site</strong>. peek requests per-origin host permission from your user gesture and starts recording.</li>
    <li>When recording is active, an <strong>in-page glow</strong> (inside a closed shadow root, excluded from peek&apos;s own capture) and a <strong>toolbar badge</strong> appear. Toggle <strong>Show recording border</strong> in the side panel to hide the glow; the badge stays visible.</li>
    <li>(Optional) Toggle <strong>Deep capture</strong> to record response bodies via <code>chrome.debugger</code>. Off by default.</li>
    <li>(Optional) Set the per-origin <strong>permission level</strong> in the side panel. Default is Level 1 (observe-only).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5. Ask your agent</h2>
  <p>
    With the MCP server connected, ask your AI client things like:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><em>&ldquo;What did I just do on this page?&rdquo;</em> (replays the latest rrweb frames)</li>
    <li><em>&ldquo;Show me the failed network requests from the last 5 minutes.&rdquo;</em></li>
    <li><em>&ldquo;What errors are in the console for example.com?&rdquo;</em></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/privacy">Privacy policy</a> &mdash; what peek records and where it lives.</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/tree/main/packages/peek-mcp#readme" rel="noopener">@peekdev/mcp README</a> &mdash; full MCP tool surface.</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/tree/main/packages/peek-cli#readme" rel="noopener">@peekdev/cli README</a> &mdash; <code>peek init</code>, <code>sessions</code>, <code>audit log</code>.</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/tree/main/packages/peek-extension#readme" rel="noopener">@peekdev/extension README</a> &mdash; side-panel UI and per-site activation.</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/blob/main/docs/qa/peek-qa.md" rel="noopener">Manual QA checklist</a> &mdash; end-to-end walk of the install path the maintainer used to verify this alpha.</li>
  </ul>

  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
    Stuck? Open an issue on
    <a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/issues" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
  </p>
</Layout>
